Cell[TextData[{
 "In other words, the average energy per degree of freedom (",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox["y",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", and ",
 StyleBox["z",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "), is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox["1", "2"], 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["k",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], 
    StyleBox["B",
     FontSlant->"Italic"]], 
   StyleBox["T",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]}]],
  InitializationCell->True,
  CellChangeTimes->{{3.9212505192469416`*^9, 3.921250534863843*^9}, {
    3.9212507356598735`*^9, 3.9212507676410656`*^9}, {3.9212508673633738`*^9, 
    3.9212509608799176`*^9}, {3.921251060924367*^9, 3.9212511124818687`*^9}, {
    3.9212511504673223`*^9, 3.921251158794492*^9}, {3.9212512029019794`*^9, 
    3.9212512716665497`*^9}, {3.921251348153563*^9, 3.921251397670518*^9}, {
    3.921328606806888*^9, 3.921328654543107*^9}, {3.921328700976661*^9, 
    3.9213287300229144`*^9}, {3.92132880468663*^9, 3.921328810904115*^9}, 
    3.9213289065831804`*^9, {3.921329027203616*^9, 3.9213292466189733`*^9}},
  ExpressionUUID->"4ae932f3-d5c0-4d06-85b9-f080e730061b"],
 ". This result can actually be shown to be general for many systems, not \
just translational degrees of freedom. Now, to obtain the average \
translational energy of the ideal gas, we first need to know the partition \
function of the entire gas (all particles), not just that of a single atom or \
molecule. We won\[CloseCurlyQuote]t derive the result here, but it can be \
shown that the partition function of an ideal gas of ",
 StyleBox["N",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " identical, indistinguishable particles is given by"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.921329253574204*^9, 3.921329426148752*^9}, {
  3.92132946358856*^9, 3.9213294642748356`*^9}, {3.9213295126042233`*^9, 
  3.9213295160252447`*^9}, {3.9213304036026354`*^9, 3.921330406516914*^9}, {
  3.9409532326019382`*^9, 
  3.940953235770214*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"d4de80a2-7bcb-48ed-97b3-\
fe98da6a3780"],

